<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,258,751]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,313,655,679]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species can be distinguished by the elongate and relatively straight aedeagal shaft (
<figureCitation box="[1323,1410,654,678]" captionStart="FIGURE 25. M" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1926,1949]" captionTargetBox="[209,1373,828,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[188,1398,804,1906]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 25. M. scalpella sp. nov. A: male pygofer lobe, lateral view; B: style, dorsal view; C: subgenital plate, ventral view; D &amp; E: aedeagus and connective, dorsal and lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206140/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Figs 
<number box="[1381,1410,654,678]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" value="25.0">25</number>
</figureCitation>
D, 
<number box="[151,181,690,714]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" value="25.0">25</number>
E).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[197,1079,726,751]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,258,751]" box="[197,1079,726,751]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,332,727,751]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Etymology.</emphasis>
This name is based on the scalpel-like shape of the aedeagal apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
